  "prompt": "What is the logic behind ISB opening another campus at Mohali? Especially now that the applicant pool has reduced this year, isn't it tantamount to diluting the brand?",
  "response": "The decision by the Indian School of Business (ISB) to open a campus in Mohali involves several strategic considerations:\n\n1. Capacity Expansion\n- Increasing student intake without overcrowding the Hyderabad campus\n- Meeting growing demand for high-quality management education\n- Providing more opportunities for potential students\n\n2. Geographic Diversification\n- Expanding presence in North India\n- Attracting talent from Punjab, Haryana, and surrounding regions\n- Creating a more geographically balanced student population\n\n3. Infrastructure and Growth\n- Leveraging modern infrastructure in the Mohali campus\n- Creating additional research and academic facilities\n- Potential for industry collaborations in the region\n\n4. Brand Strategy\n- Not necessarily diluting the brand, but extending its reach\n- Maintaining strict admission standards\n- Ensuring consistent academic quality across campuses\n\n5. Competitive Positioning\n- Responding to growing competition from other top B-schools\n- Providing more flexible learning options\n- Creating a comprehensive national footprint\n\nWhile applicant pool reduction might seem counterintuitive, ISB likely views this as a long-term strategic investment. The additional campus represents a calculated expansion rather than brand dilution, provided they maintain rigorous academic and selection standards.\n\nThese are strategic perspectives based on typical B-school expansion motivations.",
